Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 21th Weekly Dose of Optimism. Everyone alwa=
ys talks about the Christmas spirit =E2=80=94 that energy in the air in the=
 few weeks leading up to Christmas =E2=80=94 but not enough people talk abo=
ut Thanksgiving vibes. They don=E2=80=99t kick in as early, but they hit ne=
arly as hard. Let this newsletter be the official start of your Thanksgivin=
g season.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Composer [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/e728f304-eaa2-4c0a-9765-c36eee438c5d?r=3D9p0gt ]
Luck isn=E2=80=99t an investment strategy. If you=E2=80=99ve read Not Borin=
g for a while, you=E2=80=99re familiar with Composer [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/e728f304-eaa2-4c0a-9765-c36eee438c5d?r=3D9p0gt ] =E2=80=94 the in=
vestment app that let=E2=80=99s you easily build sophisticated trading stra=
tegies. Since founding its algorithmic trading platform in 2020, Composer h=
as helped over 20,000 customers trade=C2=A0100s of millions of dollars. I=
=E2=80=99m one of them =E2=80=94 after finally admitting I=E2=80=99m a terr=
ible trader, I=E2=80=99ve moved my public markets investing to Composer=E2=
=80=99s automated strategies.=20
Composer has synthesized all of this data, sifting through what works (and,=
 importantly, what=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t) to create its most powerful invest=
ing solution yet:=C2=A0Opus [ https://substack.com/redirect/e728f304-eaa2-4=
c0a-9765-c36eee438c5d?r=3D9p0gt ]. Put simply, Opus is a quantitative tool =
built on Composer=E2=80=99s vast pool of data with just one goal in mind: m=
aximize risk-adjusted returns.=C2=A0Opus by Composer=C2=A0can help you, as =
a retail investor, close the gap.
It=E2=80=99s easy to get started.=C2=A0Just choose your volatility level an=
d start investing in Opus.
(1) Artemis I Launch
=E2=80=9CWe choose to go to the moon not because it is easy but because it =
is hard.=E2=80=9D=20
Getting back to the moon has proven harder than expected. However, after tw=
o failed attempts, Artemis I successfully launched in the early hours of We=
dnesday morning. The Artemis program=E2=80=99s long-term objective is to es=
tablish a permanent basecamp on the moon to facilitate human missions to Ma=
rs. The goals of Artemis I, an uncrewed mission, are to launch the Orion sp=
acecraft into lunar orbit, carry 10 satellites into space, and prepare the =
way for Artemis II, which will perform a crewed lunar flyby. Ultimately, th=
e Artemis program is a recommitment from the U.S. that space exploration ma=
tters and a strong sign that the U.S. will play a leading role in the burge=
oning space economy. [ https://substack.com/redirect/83b0fa04-b171-4563-af4=
4-a02f4a8ac653?r=3D9p0gt ]
(2) Descript + Notion Product Releases
AI is making creative work =E2=80=94 the type of work we do here at Not Bor=
ing =E2=80=94 easier. Yesterday, two products we use on a daily basis, Desc=
ript and Notion, launched AI-powered versions of their products. Both produ=
cts, especially Descript, have relied on AI/ML for a while, but the re-vamp=
ed products rely more heavily on the Transformers flavor that has dominated=
 this recent wave of Generative AI.=20
Descript is using AI to make video recording and editing a thing everyone, =
not just video editors, can do. It=E2=80=99s already an awesome product =E2=
=80=94 we probably wouldn=E2=80=99t even do a podcast or Youtube series if =
Descript didn=E2=80=99t exist =E2=80=94 but the new AI-powered Storyboard p=
roduct looks like it will solve many of the minor frustrations we=E2=80=99v=
e had with the product.=20
For Notion, we admittedly have not gotten off the waitlist to try the produ=
ct yet (hit us up Notion folks!) but the demo video is pretty impressive, a=
nd the product is one we could easily imagine using to help create content,=
 alongside AI-powered tools we already use like re:collect [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/33593a0a-fde7-4335-bcb8-19969371bd81?r=3D9p0gt ], Lex [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/c73381b6-c14f-4bf0-a26c-e3433496fa3d?r=3D9p0gt ]=
, GPT-3 [ https://substack.com/redirect/e7b8da3b-147e-466d-a51e-deb0355cdf9=
7?r=3D9p0gt ], Metaphor [ https://substack.com/redirect/72ad5465-361f-4bbd-=
b206-4cf3e637e005?r=3D9p0gt ], and Stable Diffusion [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/05cbdd34-6f32-4c16-9013-197bc0a21695?r=3D9p0gt ].=20
Today, AI augments creativity. We=E2=80=99re a long way (although, GPT-4 co=
uld be nuts [ https://substack.com/redirect/4902e47b-5ef1-419f-b014-44216bc=
3d2a7?r=3D9p0gt ] and everything is moving really quickly) from AI replacin=
g human creativity. In a world in which creating content becomes much, much=
 easier, our bet is that truly original thinking will stand out even more.
(3) Anton Teaches Packy AI | E2 | Chinchilla [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/c0cf3956-74ef-4a3c-8a5f-7487d9af5248?r=3D9p0gt ]
Notion and Descript are just two of hundreds of examples of AI infiltrating=
 the products we know and love, or powering new products altogether. Using =
the products is a ton of fun, but I also wanted to better understand what=
=E2=80=99s happening under the hood. Anton Teaches Packy AI is my attempt t=
o ask all of the dumb questions that help me learn something better so that=
 you don=E2=80=99t have to. Anton Troynikov [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/b194a9ba-4dca-461d-be21-31a0db8c0e6e?r=3D9p0gt ], the co-founder of Chroma=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/61dd795b-4e54-4004-9ee5-3f273718dfd3?r=3D9=
p0gt ], has been in the space for over a decade, and explains everything wi=
th a mix of technical depth, historical context, inside baseball, and philo=
sophy that makes it all approachable and mind-expanding.=20
We=E2=80=99re back with our second episode of Anton Teaches Packy AI. In ou=
r first episode, Anton and Packy discussed =E2=80=9CAttention is All You Ne=
ed," the research paper which kicked off the entire Transformer Generative =
AI wave. In the second episode, we=E2=80=99re back discuss to Deep Mind=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=9CTraining Compute Optimal Large Language Models,=E2=80=9D t=
he basis for the Chinchillas model. The major insight of the research is th=
at optimal large language models should scale parameters and data proportio=
nality.
Perhaps even more exciting than the paper itself, Anton and Packy discuss t=
he politics, competitive landscape, and major players in AI, and, if the pa=
per is right =E2=80=94 where exactly we=E2=80=99re going to get all of the =
necessary data to train next generation models. Check out the conversation =
below and support our =E2=80=9CPivot to Video=E2=80=9D by subscribing to ou=
r Youtube channel.
(4) World population hits eight billion =E2=80=94 here=E2=80=99s how resear=
chers predict it will grow [ https://substack.com/redirect/371a8abd-794f-40=
cf-bb23-a1acefeed080?r=3D9p0gt ]
David Adam [ https://substack.com/redirect/b40fe0c4-dbf1-44b9-a0b7-3cbf880c=
06ab?r=3D9p0gt ] for Nature
Demographers will never be sure whether 15 November really was the Day of E=
ight Billion, as the UN has named it, but they do agree on one thing. Altho=
ugh the human population has grown rapidly, that growth is slowing =E2=80=
=94 and, within a few decades, Earth=E2=80=99s population will begin to shr=
ink.
As of Tuesday, there are (unofficially) 8 billion of us here on Earth.=20
Since 1950, the world=E2=80=99s population has grown by nearly 4x largely d=
ue to medical advancements, lower mortality rates, and agricultural product=
ivity. Just another reminder that, despite the doom and gloom headlines, th=
e important things have gotten seriously better over the last few generatio=
ns. Much of this population growth has occured in just two countries =E2=80=
=94 China and India =E2=80=94 which combined have increased their populatio=
ns by over 1.5 billion since 1950.=20
But researchers predict that the population boom times are coming to end; g=
rowth has already slowed and population may actually start shrinking in fif=
ty years, once we cross the 10 billion people mark. The likelihood of popul=
ation collapse, and the impact of that collapse, is highly disputed. Elon h=
as called lower birth rates a bigger risk to civilization than climate chan=
ge [ https://substack.com/redirect/a212b0f9-4327-40e8-9d3b-784d2f0493bc?r=
=3D9p0gt ], while other=E2=80=99s have pointed out that slowing growth does=
 not equate to population collapse [ https://substack.com/redirect/900ed44b=
-d455-41d2-ac0a-6f40e7b32bd5?r=3D9p0gt ]. We=E2=80=99re particularly intere=
sted in the incredible work being done in biotech to extend the health span=
s of those of us lucky enough to count ourselves among Earth=E2=80=99s 8 bi=
llion living people.=20
How you like them apples, Malthus?
(5) Things could be better [ https://substack.com/redirect/0a611809-90d4-4b=
4b-82d0-3ba8c2cd754f?r=3D9p0gt ]
From Adam Mastroianni [ https://substack.com/redirect/1068fbd1-755f-466e-8d=
6b-c64bc0d3c259?r=3D9p0gt ] and Ethan Ludwin-Peery [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/6706d8c8-f539-495f-a672-1984efb5ff0b?r=3D9p0gt ], h/t Alice Albrech=
t [ https://substack.com/redirect/fa42d254-3ac0-4dcf-b5af-f2283b8c0ef5?r=3D=
9p0gt ]
Overall, it seems, human imagination has a bias: when people imagine how th=
ings could be, they imagine how things could be better.
Two researches ran eight studies to determine how people perceive =E2=80=9C=
good=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cbad.=E2=80=9D The major finding: when people ima=
gine how things could be different, they almost always imagine how things c=
ould be better. Controlling for a bunch of different factors, such as how t=
he question is phrased, language, pre-disposition, the results were consist=
ent: people are biased towards imagining how things could be better. People=
 imagine how things could be better even when it=E2=80=99s easier to imagin=
e how things could be worse.
Quick example: how could your phone be different? Participants answered:
=E2=80=9CIt could be waterproof=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CMy phone could be bendable and flexible=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CBrighter screen=E2=80=9D
Despite the fact that the average cellphone today is already pretty waterpr=
oof, durable, and has a bright screen=E2=80=A6when asked how the phone coul=
d be different, they want more waterpoofness, durableness, and brightness. =
Other ways your phone could be different:
It could not have access to the internet
It could only work outside
It can=E2=80=99t send text messages
These changes would surely make today=E2=80=99s phone more different, but t=
hese would also be downgrades. People imagine the potential upgrades before=
 the downgrades.
How does this apply to us? Well for one, it means we=E2=80=99ll always have=
 readers of The Weekly Dose of Optimism. People are looking for the ways in=
 which the world can be better, and that=E2=80=99s the type of news we shar=
e here at Not Boring. But more importantly, understanding this bias can pot=
entially make us more appreciative of the way things are. Our bias towards =
=E2=80=9Cdifferent =3D better=E2=80=9D is probably one of the human charact=
eristics that drives towards progress more than any other, but at the same =
time recognizing different could =3D worse should leave us somewhat ore opt=
imistic about the the current state of things.
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox 9am E=
ST on Monday morning with an essay we=E2=80=99ve been working on for a few =
weeks.
Packy

