rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Alice Albrec=
ht</a></em></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin:=
 20px 0;"><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>Overall, it seems, human imagina=
tion has a bias: when people imagine how things could be, they imagine how =
things could be better.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #404040; fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Two researches=
 ran eight studies to determine how people perceive &#8220;good&#8221; and =
&#8220;bad.&#8221; </span><strong>The major finding:</strong><span> when pe=
ople imagine how things could be </span><em><strong>different, </strong></e=
m><span>they almost always imagine how things could be </span><em><strong>b=
etter. </strong></em><span>Controlling for a bunch of different factors, su=
ch as how the question is phrased, language, pre-disposition, the results w=
ere consistent: people are biased towards imagining how things could be </s=
pan><em>better</em><span>. People imagine how things could be </span><em>be=
tter </em><span>even when it&#8217;s easier to imagine how things could be =
worse.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Quick example: </span><em>how could your p=
hone be different? </em><span>Participants answered:</span></p><ul style=3D=
"margin-top: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special=
-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: #404040; font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4=
px;">&#8220;It could be waterproof&#8221;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px =
0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; =
color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-botto=
m: 0; padding-left: 4px;">&#8220;My phone could be bendable and flexible&#8=
221;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;=
"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">&#8220;Brig=
hter screen&#8221;</p></li></ul><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Despite the fact that the a=
verage cellphone today is already pretty waterproof, durable, and has a bri=
ght screen&#8230;when asked how the phone could be </span><em>different</em=
><span>, they want more waterpoofness, durableness, and brightness. Other w=
ays your phone could be </span><em>different</em><span>:</span></p><ul styl=
e=3D"margin-top: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-spe=
cial-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: #404040; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-lef=
t: 4px;">It could not have access to the internet</p></li><li style=3D"marg=
in: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: bord=
er-box; color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; marg=
in-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">It could only work outside</p></li><li st=
yle=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-s=
izing: border-box; color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">It can&#8217;t send text messa=
ges</p></li></ul><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>These changes would surely make today&#821=
7;s phone more </span><em>different, </em><span>but these would also be dow=
ngrades. People imagine the potential upgrades before the downgrades.</span=
></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>How does this apply to us? Well for one, it means we&#=
8217;ll always have readers of </span><em>The Weekly Dose of Optimism. </em=
><span>People are looking for the ways in which the world can be better, an=
d that&#8217;s the type of news we share here at Not Boring. But more impor=
tantly, understanding this bias can potentially make us more appreciative o=
f the way things are. Our bias towards &#8220;different =3D better&#8221; i=
s probably one of the human characteristics that drives towards progress mo=
re than any other, but at the same time recognizing different could =3D wor=
se should leave us somewhat ore optimistic about the the current state of t=
hings.</span></p><div style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;"><hr sty=
le=3D"background: #e0e0e0; border: none; height: 1px; margin: 32px 0; paddi=
ng: 0;"></div><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s all for this week. We&#8217;ll be back=
 in your inbox 9am EST on Monday morning with an essay we&#8217;ve been wor=
